Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Housing Finance, Sasini Are Active

-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 
2011-03-02T14:51:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-02/sub-saharan-african-stocks-housing-finance-sasini-are-active.html
  Kenya ’s All-Share Index retreated
for a third day, losing 0.3 percent to close at 77.02 by 3 p.m.
in Nairobi.  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index fell 0.7 percent to
25,686.44 by 2:32 p.m. in Lagos, a sixth day of declines.
Namibia’s FTSE  Namibia Overall Index  dropped 0.1 percent to
888.61 by 4:28 p.m. in Windhoek while the Ghana Stock Exchange
Composite Index retreated 0.7 percent to 1,042, a second day of
decreases. Mauritius’s market was closed for a public holiday.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Housing Finance Co. (HFCL KN), Kenya’s only publicly traded
mortgage lender, advanced to the highest in more than four
months, adding 50 cents, or 1.7 percent, to close at 29.75
shillings after saying full-year profit surged to 379.5 million
shillings ($4.58 million) in the 12 months through December from
234.2 million shillings a year earlier.    Sasini Ltd . (STCL KN), a Kenyan tea and coffee grower, fell
to a one-year low, losing 80 cents, or 7.1 percent, to 10.55
shillings. African tea prices retreated for the first week in
four at a weekly sale in Mombasa, Kenya, declining to an average
of $2.79 a kilogram from $2.85 a week earlier, Tea Brokers East  Africa  Ltd. said in an e-mailed statement yesterday. Kenya is
world’s biggest exporter of black tea.  Kenya’s benchmark coffee grade, AA, fell 12 percent at an
auction yesterday after the quality of the beans declined, the
Nairobi Coffee Exchange said in an e-mailed statement yesterday.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Eric Ombok in Nairobi at 
